        id: 'rp-1',
        title: 'Principles in Creative Subjects',
        content: '<h3>What is Restorative Practice?</h3><p>Restorative practice is an approach that prioritises relationships, responsibility, and repairing harm rather than punishment. In Scottish education, it aligns with Getting it Right for Every Child (GIRFEC), the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child (UNCRC), and rights-based approaches.</p><h3>Why It Matters in Expressive Arts</h3><p>In Drama, Art and Photography, pupils work collaboratively: devising in groups, sharing studio space, using shared equipment, and giving peer feedback. Conflict is inevitable—disputes over roles, disagreements about creative decisions, arguments over materials or camera time, exclusion from a group. Restorative practice offers a way to address these incidents that rebuilds relationships and keeps learning moving forward.</p><h3>Key Principles</h3><p><strong>Fair Process</strong>: Pupils are involved in decisions that affect them. In Drama, when a group decides how to divide tasks, everyone has a say. In Art, when setting up workspace norms, pupils contribute. Fair process increases buy-in and reduces resentment.</p><p><strong>High Challenge, High Support</strong>: Hold high expectations while providing the support needed to meet them. A pupil struggling with confidence in Drama still needs to be stretched—perhaps through a smaller role first, or script-writing alongside performing.</p><p><strong>Working With, Not Doing To</strong>: Avoid imposing solutions. Instead, work with pupils to find ways forward. When a devising group breaks down, a restorative conversation helps pupils hear each other and agree how to proceed—rather than the teacher simply reassigning roles.</p><h3>Reflective Question</h3><p>Think of a recent conflict in your Drama, Art or Photography class. How might a restorative approach have changed the outcome?</p>',
