        id: 'rp-3',
        title: 'Repairing Harm in Group Work',
        content: '<h3>When Harm Occurs</h3><p>When relationships break down—falling out in a devising group, exclusion in Art, conflict during a photo shoot—restorative circles or small-group conversations can repair harm and restore the conditions for learning.</p><h3>Structure of a Restorative Circle</h3><p>Everyone has a turn to speak without interruption. Use a talking object (pen, prop) so only the holder speaks. The focus is on: <strong>impact</strong> (how people were affected) and <strong>what is needed to move on</strong>.</p><p>In Drama, this might mean agreeing new rehearsal norms: "We will listen when someone is presenting." "We will share roles fairly." In Art, re-establishing trust for collaborative work: "We will ask before using someone\'s materials." In Photography, agreeing how to share equipment and include everyone in planning.</p><h3>Facilitating the Circle</h3><p>As the teacher, you facilitate—you do not impose solutions. Ask the restorative questions. If pupils struggle, offer prompts: "What would help you feel included?" "What do you need from the group?" Write down agreed actions and revisit them.</p><h3>Follow-Up</h3><p>Follow-up is essential. Check in later: "How is it going with the agreement you made?" If something is not holding, reconvene. Some pupils may need additional support (e.g. ASN, nurture) alongside restorative work.</p><h3>Key Takeaway</h3><p>Restorative practice is not a one-off conversation. It is part of a classroom culture where relationships are valued, harm is addressed, and pupils are supported to take responsibility and repair.</p>',
