        id: 'bm-1',
        title: 'Prevention in Practical Spaces',
        content: '<h3>Behaviour is Best Managed Through Prevention</h3><p>Reactive behaviour management—constantly addressing low-level disruption—is exhausting and less effective than preventing problems before they start. In Drama, Art and Photography, practical spaces have specific challenges: movement, equipment, noise, group work.</p><h3>Clear Routines</h3><p>Establish and teach routines explicitly:</p><ul><li><strong>Entry:</strong> How do pupils enter the drama studio? Where do bags go? What does "ready" look like?</li><li><strong>Equipment:</strong> How do we get out and put away materials? In Art, who collects paint, brushes, paper? In Photography, how do we check out cameras?</li><li><strong>Signals for attention:</strong> Freeze, lights off, clap pattern, hand up—pick one and use it consistently.</li><li><strong>Exit:</strong> How do we finish? Tidy, feedback, dismissal.</li></ul><h3>Non-Negotiables</h3><p>Identify your non-negotiables: no running in the studio, safe use of materials (especially in Art and darkroom), listening when others perform or present. Teach these in the first lessons and rehearse them. "When someone is performing, we show respect by..."</p><h3>Predict Problem Points</h3><p>Transitions, equipment handouts, waiting times, and group formation are predictable problem points. Plan for them: time limits, visual timers, structured roles ("Equipment monitor"), activities for those waiting. In Photography, if only a few can use cameras at once, what do others do?</p><h3>Drama-Specific</h3><p>In Drama, establish "performance mode"—when we are audience, we watch and listen. Rehearse moving from practical to discussion and back. Define boundaries: what is acceptable in role vs. out of role.</p><h3>Reflective Question</h3><p>List three predictable problem points in your next lesson. How will you plan for them?</p>',
