        id: 'bm-2',
        title: 'Interventions and Consistency',
        content: '<h3>When Behaviour Slips</h3><p>Despite prevention, behaviour will sometimes slip. Use a graduated approach. Start with the least intrusive interventions:</p><ul><li><strong>Proximity:</strong> Move near the pupil.</li><li><strong>Quiet word:</strong> "You need to focus on your blocking" rather than announcing across the room.</li><li><strong>Choice:</strong> "You can work quietly here or move to that table."</li><li><strong>Redirect:</strong> "What should you be doing right now?"</li></ul><p>Avoid public confrontations that escalate. A challenge in front of peers can trigger defensiveness. A quiet, private conversation is more likely to succeed.</p><h3>Consistency is Vital</h3><p>Same rules in Drama, Art and Photography. Same follow-through. If "phones away" is the rule, it applies in the darkroom too. Inconsistent enforcement undermines authority and confuses pupils. Agree department norms with colleagues and stick to them.</p><h3>De-escalation</h3><p>If a pupil is becoming agitated, de-escalate: lower your voice, give wait time, offer a way out ("Take a minute in the corridor, then come back when you\'re ready"). Avoid cornering, raising your voice, or threatening consequences in the heat of the moment.</p><h3>Know Your Escalation Path</h3><p>Know the school\'s behaviour policy and your escalation path: warning, move, referral. Use the minimum necessary. Document when needed for CASS, support plans, or parents. In practical subjects, removing a pupil may be necessary for safety—but it should be calm and consistent, not reactive.</p><h3>Key Takeaway</h3><p>Low-level first. Consistent follow-through. De-escalate when needed. Document when required.</p>',
