        id: 'bm-3',
        title: 'Subject-Specific Considerations',
        content: '<h3>Drama Studio</h3><p>The drama studio is a space for movement, expression and risk-taking. Establish clear boundaries: physical space (stage vs. audience), behaviour in role vs. out of role, and safe physical contact. Warm-ups and cool-downs structure the start and end. If pupils use props or costume, set norms for handling and returning them.</p><h3>Art Room</h3><p>Art rooms have hazards: paint, sharp tools, kilns, chemicals. Behaviour management is also safety management. Teach safe use explicitly. Assign roles: who cleans brushes, who checks sinks. Manage space: ensure clear walkways, no bags in thoroughfares. For collaborative murals or group work, agree how space and materials are shared.</p><h3>Darkroom and Photography</h3><p>Darkrooms require strict routines: lights off, no phones (light leaks), safe chemical handling. In digital photography, equipment is expensive and tempting. Clear rules for camera use, storage and accountability. Group shoots need planning: who directs, who shoots, how decisions are made.</p><h3>Different Spaces, Same Principles</h3><p>Routines, non-negotiables, predictability. Adapt the content to the space, but the principles of prevention and consistency apply across all three.</p>',
