        id: 'ef-2',
        title: 'Verbal and Written Feedback in Creative Contexts',
        content: '<h3>Verbal Feedback</h3><p>Verbal feedback works particularly well during practical work. It is immediate and can be tailored in the moment. In Drama: "That blocking choice shows the power dynamic—keep that." "Your eye contact with the audience there was strong." In Art: "Your layering there is strengthening the composition." "Try varying your brush pressure for more texture." In Photography: "Good use of leading lines." "Consider adjusting the exposure for the highlights."</p><p>Verbal feedback can be recorded for evidence: "VF: discussed use of tone and next steps for blending." Some departments use stamps or codes to indicate verbal feedback has been given.</p><h3>Written Feedback</h3><p>Written feedback should be concise and focused. Avoid overwhelming pupils with long paragraphs. One or two foci per piece is enough. Balance acknowledgment of strengths with clear next steps. Use highlighters or codes if your department has agreed them (e.g. green = strength, pink = improve).</p><h3>Feed-Forward</h3><p>In portfolios, consider feed-forward: what to do in the <em>next</em> piece, not only correcting the last one. "In your next expressive piece, focus on building tone gradually" is more useful than a long list of errors on the previous work.</p><h3>Pupil Response</h3><p>Feedback is only useful if pupils engage with it. Build in time for pupils to respond: improve a section, add a note, attempt the suggested technique. "What will you do differently next time?" Make feedback a dialogue.</p>',
