        content: '<h3>Peer Feedback in Expressive Arts</h3><p>Peer feedback develops critical skills and reduces the teacher\'s marking load. Teach pupils how to give feedback: use success criteria as a framework, model "What worked well" and "Even better if" (WWW/EBI), and establish norms ("Be specific", "Be kind").</p><p>In Drama, pupils can feed back on performances using the same criteria they are assessed on. In Art, peer critique of work in progress can help. In Photography, pupils can comment on each other\'s images using technical and compositional vocabulary.</p><h3>Self-Assessment</h3><p>Self-assessment encourages reflection. "Which success criterion have you met? Which are you still working on?" In Drama, written evaluations after performance. In Art, annotations in sketchbooks. In Photography, captions or reflections on intent. Pupils who can accurately self-assess are better placed to improve.</p><h3>Quality of Peer and Self-Assessment</h3><p>Initially, peer and self-assessment may be shallow. Teach it explicitly: what does "specific" look like? Give sentence starters. "One strength was... because..." "To improve, I could..." Over time, quality improves.</p>',
