        id: 'ret-1',
        title: 'Retrieval in Practical Lessons',
        content: '<h3>What is Retrieval Practice?</h3><p>Retrieval practice is the act of recalling information from memory. Research shows that the act of retrieval strengthens memory more than re-reading or re-watching. In other words, testing is learning—when it is low-stakes and used to support recall, not to judge.</p><h3>In Expressive Arts</h3><p>We have a lot of vocabulary and concepts to recall: Drama (proxemics, blocking, levels, gesture, stimulus, conventions), Art (elements of art, colour theory, composition, tone, line), Photography (aperture, shutter speed, ISO, depth of field, rule of thirds). Retrieval practice helps pupils remember these so they can use them in practical work and in evaluation.</p><h3>Low-Stakes</h3><p>Retrieval practice should be low-stakes: no grading, or minimal impact on grades. The goal is recall, not punishment. Pupils should feel safe to have a go. Use it as starters, quick checks during demos, or plenaries.</p><h3>Spacing</h3><p>Spacing—revisiting information across lessons and weeks—improves long-term retention. Do not just retrieve once; bring back key terms in later lessons. "We used this last week—what was it?"</p><h3>Methods</h3><p>Flashcards, mini-whiteboards, quick verbal rounds, "Do Now" tasks, multiple-choice checks. Keep it short: 3–5 minutes is often enough.</p>',
