        content: '<h3>Do Now Starters</h3><p>Start lessons with quick retrieval: "Write three Drama terms we used last week." "Draw the colour wheel from memory." "Label this diagram: aperture, shutter, ISO." Give a time limit (2–3 minutes) and avoid making it feel like a test.</p><h3>During Practical Work</h3><p>Quick verbal checks: "What do we mean by blocking?" "What is contrast in photography?" "Which element of art are you using here?" Weave retrieval into the flow of the lesson.</p><h3>Plenaries</h3><p>End with retrieval: "In 30 seconds, write everything you can remember about..." Pair-share so pupils can add to each other\'s lists. Show-me boards keep it low-pressure and allow you to see who has recalled what.</p><h3>Linking Retrieval to Practice</h3><p>Retrieval is most effective when it connects to application. After recalling "levels" in Drama, pupils use levels in the next scene. After recalling "composition" in Art, they apply it in their next sketch. "We just recalled depth of field—now use it in your next three shots."</p><h3>Vocabulary Banks</h3><p>Maintain word mats or vocabulary lists that pupils can refer to. Use them for retrieval: "Without looking, what does proxemics mean?" Then they can check. Over time, reduce support so they rely on memory.</p>',
