        content: '<h3>Flexible Grouping</h3><p>Group pupils differently for different purposes: sometimes by readiness (similar level), sometimes by interest (choice of stimulus in Drama, theme in Art), sometimes mixed (peer support). In Drama, rotate pairs and trios. In Art, use peer support: "Explain to your partner how you mixed that colour." In Photography, buddy less confident pupils with those confident with equipment.</p><h3>Scaffolding</h3><p>Model first, then guided practice, then independent. Provide resource banks: word mats for Drama vocabulary, step-by-step guides for darkroom use, exemplars for portfolio work. Remove scaffolds gradually as pupils become more confident. Do not over-scaffold for those who can work independently.</p><h3>Extension Tasks</h3><p>Plan extension tasks so no one is left waiting. In Drama: "If you have finished blocking, add a soundscape." In Art: "If you have completed the main task, develop a second piece using a different media." In Photography: "If you have your five shots, experiment with editing."</p><h3>Support Tasks</h3><p>Plan support so no one is left behind. Pre-teach vocabulary. Provide sentence starters. Break tasks into smaller steps. Use visual supports. Know your pupils and plan accordingly.</p>',
