        title: 'Flexible Grouping and Scaffolding',
        content: '<h3>Flexible Grouping in Creative Contexts</h3><p>Vary who leads and who follows. In Drama, rotate who leads warm-ups or who presents the group\'s idea. In Art, mix pairs for peer critique so different pupils work together. In Photography, vary who operates the camera or directs the shoot. This develops leadership and ensures no one is always in the same role.</p><h3>Scaffolding</h3><p>Provide sentence starters for written evaluation in Drama: "The use of... effectively showed..." Offer templates for artist research in Art. Give checklists for portfolio organisation. As pupils improve, reduce support. Do not leave scaffolds in place longer than needed.</p><h3>Knowing When to Push</h3><p>Adaptive teaching also means knowing when to push. If a pupil can do more, extend the challenge rather than over-scaffolding. Sometimes the right response is higher demand, not more support. Observe, assess, and adjust.</p><h3>Balance</h3><p>Balance support and challenge. Too much support can limit growth. Too much challenge without support can cause disengagement. Adaptive teaching is about finding that balance for each pupil, in each moment.</p>',
